2020 was a year that has pushed us in innumerable ways. Over at The Loveland Foundation we have been unrelenting in our efforts to get mental health care access to as many Black women and girls as possible.
•
My team and I are gearing up for what we hope is a successful Giving Tuesday push tomorrow as we seek raise more funds which equals more hours of therapy for our recipients. I hope you’ll consider @thelovelandfoundation as part of your 2020 community investment.
•
We asked our cohort members and therapists to tell us: Why does your mental health matter? We are excited to share with you some of their responses.
•
I am beyond proud of the Black women and girls who are prioritizing their mental health this year.
•
I am so grateful to and proud of you all for loving on yourselves, cherishing yourselves and prioritizing your wellbeing this year and beyond.
•

node.text:
In the time between when the pandemic began and when the protests began I spent time every weekday reading stories to little ones who may have tuned in.
•
As someone without children I often feel like it’s my obligation to be part of the “village” that helps other‘s in providing care for theirs. The reading series I did had been my way of showing up where I can and where I feel led to.
•
It’s the same now in this continued fight against injustice and this particular fight against police brutality — we all have to show up whenever and however and with every ounce of our power, heart and intention.
•
I wanted to offer this reading I did just a few weeks ago by Faith Ringgold as a soft space in your day — whenever this post may pop up on your feed.
•
I say over and over my healing has always been found in Black women and book written and illustrated by Faith Ringgold has held my heart tenderly since my own mama read it to me as a little girl. Today Cassie and her dreams and her words and her hopes for her people still sound like the sweetest thing to my ears and encompasses the passions I hold within me.
•
Take a breath, listen to the story, continue to show up and never back down.
•
If you love this book you can purchase it from my bookstore @elizabethsofakron and a parentage of proceeds will go to @thelovelandfoundation.

Swipe 🥨 This is an appreciation post for this body of mine. Descriptors of my 5'9" frame include: Tall, brown, fat, soft, and curvy. I love my body. I love the way it moves when I dance, the way it has carried me for 32 years, and the way it changes over time.
•
A few years ago I wrote a piece for @harpersbazaarus about my frustrations around the way people called this shoot “brave”. I didn’t feel brave — I needn’t be, I wasn’t running into a burning building! What I actually felt was sexy and joyous. Then calling me brave said more about their perceptions of my fat body than anything having to do with my own “courage” to be bare.
•
photo by my sweet sweet friend @sarahbahbah 
•
You can head to the link in my bio to read the full essay.
•
For more of my writing you can head to my blog AnEternalSunday.com where my comments are open and I’m so ready to be in community with you all over there. (link in bio as well)

May be an image of text that says 'I was so proud and excited about the outcome of the shoot that almost immediately I decided to put the photo on social media. Posting such a revealing and intimate take on who I am as a woman wasn't a point of contention, but instead a chance to celebrate a side of me that isn't always captured. My followers had seen the depths of my mind, so this body shouldn't have rocked too many boats.'.

Photo by Rachel Elizabeth Cargle on July 13, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'But then there was something else I noticed. I was getting dozens of comments with the best of intentions under the guise of encouragement, but they missed the mark- quite a bit. Comment after comment told me how brave I was for posting nude photos of myself. I was confused, and a little offended. What is brave about my existing happily in my body? What is brave about showing up for my love of self, instead of for the gaze of white or male beauty standards? What is brave about being seen? Being visible?'.

node.text:
Swipe 🌿 A Sunday Moodboard +  my new blog.
•
I shared with you all last week the feelings I’d been swimming in around social platforms. How disenchanting it’s all become. About how I wanted to reimagine the way I am in community.
•
So I did. I reimagined. You can head to the link in my bio and find it: ‘Something Like An Eternal Sunday’. It’s a space where my writing can live with some softness and simplicity. See you there?
•
The first six posts are published for you. These are all writings done by previous and varying versions of myself. I hope you read them and perhaps add some texture to the ways you engage with me and my work. I share my entry essay to Columbia and a letter I wrote to myself in 2017. I share a piece where I questioned humanity on the NYC subway and I share the essay on the song my mother used to hum for me — an audio of the song was recorded by my mother and you listen to her love for me.
•
Head over, spend a few moments of YOUR soft Sunday reading my words and let me know what you think.
•
Im settling into very very new versions of myself. Im looking forward to growing along with you — just not so much in these little squares anymore. Join me IRL and online via my brands @thegreatunlearn & @tguyounglearners & @elizabethsofakron & @richauntiesupreme. These are places here we gather and we build and we learn and we grow. I’m not here to make content. I want to build community. I hope you’ll join me off the timeline. My blog is a really good place to start. 
•
In the meantime this set of photos are highlights that have been on my mind. Gifts from my garden, the birdsong that melted my heart this morning, smiles from lovers and friends, solo lunches in Chinatown and some art literature I can’t get enough of.
•
See you around 💫
•
But before you go: What sweetness found it’s way into your Sunday today?

node.text:
Social media is disenchanting me  more and more.

I’m leaning into slow and simple and soft and easeful. 

I’m a writer. I’m an entrepreneur. I’m a creative. I’m a friend. Im a lover. I’m a daughter. I’m an auntie. I’m a reader. I’m a neighbor. I’m a student. I’m a teacher. 

Influencer & a content creator just don’t fit me well.

I’m a Black girl curating a good life for me. Im not seeking for this lifetime of mine to simply be seen or validated. I want it to be lived — indulgently. Im uninterested in only being gazed upon in small squares.

I feel things shifting in me.

I’m craving something like an eternal Sunday.
🌿

I said “eternal Sunday” on a whim while writing this but it is such a spot on concept for the soft space I’m trying to create. I’m thinking of indulging in starting a blog where I can write long form and share my ideas and my insights and all the good things happening in my world — And IG will instead be a place where I signal boost what’s happening in my real world instead of the platform being where it all resides. Would you be interested in following my work & check in with me outside this platform? I have a book coming soon, many exciting partnerships to share and lots of delicious workshops, conversations and lectures on my horizon that I’d continue to let you know about on your timeline — but the roots of my no longer have space to spread in these boxes. Maybe Ill just lost in Sunday’s to touch base, catch up? Let me know your thoughts 🧡 Just some active reimagining with you all this morning. I’m so happy you’re here and I don’t take this community for granted one bit….

node.text:
I’ve decided that this summer I am gifting myself a soft, sweet, succulent one. 

I’m picnicking in the park, I’m exploring the book piles I have resting on my shelf, I’m going to pick strawberries in the fields upstate, I’m indulging in the warmth of a lover in the cool evenings. 

I’m writing handwritten letters to old friends, I’m taking mid day naps in sun puddles on my terrace, I’m waking up early and sipping coffee on the park bench, I’m packing light for trips to the vineyard and trips to sea. 

I’m dancing in the moonlight on sands on other coasts, I’m eating big bowls of salads for lunch and ice cream for dinner. I’m going to revel in my bronzed skin, I’m going to say yes only to the things that thrill me and let no be a complete sentence where my heart finds necessary. 

I’m going to make rest a verb and healing a decree. I will write in my journal while on sailboats and I will read rocking lightly in a hammock under a tree.

I don’t know if gifting myself an entire season is an option but I’ve always let my curiosity prove the possibilities.

What are some of your favorite parts of the summer months that you refuse to let pass you by this year?

Some mantras on rest — from the coziness of my bed to yours:
•
1. There is no martyrdom in the exhausted
🌿
2. My body and being is a universe in itself. I offer myself seasons for rest, growth, harvest. Today it is rest.
🌿
3. I choose proactive rest. Instead of crumbling of exhaustion when I’m tired, I will rest up and offer myself the energy to go about my day/month/year.
🌿
4. Rest is not a reward that I only access once I’ve proven ‘worthy’. It is my birthright.
🌿

I’ve been loving the little corner of heaven that exists in soil of my terrace garden. Being in such close relationship with tangible growth and intention is a brilliant dance.
•
I’ve been finding all the ways I can engage with & indulge in its glory. Not wanting even the smallest leaf to feel that the work is took to burst from the seed had been all for naught.
•
Last week I made a few jars of Mint Sun Tea. A jar for myself and another as a gift for someone I was visiting with that day. Swipe to see!
•
A sweet harmony of water, mint, honey and the deep love of earths sunshine — I can’t express enough how special this tea is from picking the leaves to taking the first sip. Enjoy:
•
Mint Sun Tea 
🌿
mint leaves
honey
water
mason jar
sunshine
•
Choose a mason jar that reflects the amount of tea you’d like to have. Use filtered water to fill the jar 3/4 of the way. Mix a spoonful (or more) of honey into the water, perhaps with a fork or whisk to help it dissolve. Pick and wash your mint leaves (as much as you’d like, more for deeper flavor) and chop or simply tear them. Take a moment to hold them in your hands and inhale their aroma — life is sweet.
•
Place you me mint leaves in the honey water and close the jar tightly. Take a moment of gratitude or intention. Walk your jar outdoors (or a open air windowsill would work) to the biggest puddle of sun your space offers and let it rest there for several hours — allowing the sun to brew the mint tea. Once you decide to enjoy, strain the mint leaves from the tea and indulge. I loved sipping this warm and it was delicious after sitting in the fridge as well!
•
What do you have growing over in your little corner of the world?
